+It seems that your script is using the AIFoundryClient, but it appears that you may need to use the AIProjectClient instead, along with the correct imports and authentication setup. Here's how to adjust your code based on the information retrieved:
+
+Update Your Imports: You should use AIProjectClient and DefaultAzureCredential for authentication.
+
+Correcting the Code: Here's an updated version of your script:
+
+import os
+from azure.ai.projects import AIProjectClient
+from azure.identity import DefaultAzureCredential
+
+# Set up your project endpoint
+project_endpoint = os.environ["PROJECT_ENDPOINT"]  # Ensure the PROJECT_ENDPOINT environment variable is set
+
+# Initialize client
+project_client = AIProjectClient(
+    endpoint=project_endpoint,
+    credential=DefaultAzureCredential(),
+)
+
+# Deploy your agent
+agent = project_client.agents.create_agent(
+    model="gpt-4o",  # Your deployment name
+    name="mmidnight",  # Your agent name
+    instructions="""You are a Windows 11 system repair specialist focused on fixing service dependencies and system errors.
+    You have access to ESET System Inspector logs and can analyze system crashes."""
+)
+
+print("Agent deployed successfully!")
+Setting Environment Variables: Ensure that the PROJECT_ENDPOINT environment variable is set with the correct endpoint for your project, which you can find in the project overview in the Azure AI Foundry portal.
+
+Authentication: Remember to run az login in your command line to authenticate your Azure account before running your script.
+
+This correction should help resolve the import error and allow you to deploy your agent correctly. If you encounter any new issues or have further questions, feel free to ask! For additional details, you can refer to the Azure AI Foundry documentation 1.

